            ],
            [
                'title' => 'Understanding Customs Clearance: A Complete Guide for International Shippers',
                'slug' => Str::slug('Understanding Customs Clearance: A Complete Guide for International Shippers'),
                'excerpt' => 'Customs clearance is one of the most misunderstood parts of international shipping. This guide explains the process, required documents, and how to avoid common delays.',
                'body' => '<p>Every international shipment must pass through customs at the destination country before it can be delivered. Customs authorities inspect shipments to verify declared contents, assess applicable duties and taxes, and ensure no prohibited items enter the country. Understanding this process is key to avoiding costly delays and unexpected fees.</p><p>The most important document in the customs process is the commercial invoice or customs declaration. This document must accurately list every item in the shipment, including a description, quantity, country of origin, and declared value in the destination currency. Undervaluing goods to avoid duties is illegal and can result in seizure, fines, and permanent bans from shipping to certain countries.</p><p>Different countries have different duty thresholds — also called de minimis values. In the United States, shipments valued under $800 generally clear customs without duty. In the European Union, the threshold is as low as €150 for commercial goods. Fast Express Shipping provides a country-specific duties estimator in your dashboard to help you anticipate costs before shipping.</p><p>Customs clearance typically takes 1–3 business days for standard shipments with complete documentation. Delays are most commonly caused by missing or inaccurate paperwork, restricted item categories, or random inspection queues. Our team of customs specialists reviews all international shipment declarations before submission to minimize the risk of holds.</p><p>If your shipment is held at customs, our support team will contact you immediately with the specific reason and required action. In most cases, providing a supplementary document or paying assessed duties resolves the hold within 24 hours. Visit our Help Center for country-specific customs guides and prohibited items lists.</p>',
                'published_at' => Carbon::now()->subDays(25),
                'is_published' => true,
            ],
