            ],
            [
                'title' => 'How to Ship Fragile Items: Professional Tips from Our Logistics Team',
                'slug' => Str::slug('How to Ship Fragile Items: Professional Tips from Our Logistics Team'),
                'excerpt' => 'Shipping fragile items successfully requires the right materials, technique, and service selection. Our logistics team shares professional packing tips to protect your valuables.',
                'body' => '<p>Fragile shipments — glassware, ceramics, electronics, artwork, and scientific instruments — require a different approach than standard packaging. The goal is not just to cushion the item, but to create a package that can survive a 1-meter drop onto a hard surface without damage. That is the real-world test every package should be able to pass before it leaves your hands.</p><p>Start with a new, double-walled corrugated box sized appropriately for your item plus at least 5 cm of cushioning on all sides. Wrap the item itself in a minimum of three layers of bubble wrap, paying special attention to corners and protruding parts. Secure the bubble wrap with tape so it cannot unwrap during transit. For especially delicate items like thin glass or precision instruments, consider custom foam inserts cut to the shape of the item.</p><p>Void fill — the material that fills empty space inside the box — is critical. Packing peanuts, air pillows, and foam sheets all work well. The item should be immobile when you seal and shake the box. Place a strip of cushioning material directly under the item and on top of it before closing the lid. Heavier items should be packed at the bottom of the box.</p><p>When selecting a service level, we recommend Express or Overnight for high-value fragile items. These service tiers receive priority handling and involve fewer transfers between facilities, which directly reduces the number of times a package is moved. Add the signature required option to ensure the package is personally received rather than left unattended.</p><p>Declare the accurate value of your fragile items and consider adding shipping insurance. If the worst happens, having proper coverage means a claim can be processed quickly. Our team is available before shipping to advise on the appropriate insurance level for your specific items.</p>',
                'published_at' => Carbon::now()->subDays(72),
                'is_published' => true,
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'Understanding Declared Value and Shipping Insurance',
                'slug' => Str::slug('Understanding Declared Value and Shipping Insurance'),
                'excerpt' => 'Declared value and shipping insurance are often confused, but they serve different purposes. Here is what you need to know to protect your shipments.',
                'body' => '<p>When you submit a shipment request with Fast Express Shipping, you are asked to declare the value of your package contents. This declared value is not the same as insurance — it is a statement of what the goods are worth for customs purposes and as a baseline for liability calculations. Understanding the difference between the two can save you significant money in the event of a claim.</p><p>The declared value establishes the upper limit of carrier liability in case of loss or damage. Most standard shipping contracts, including ours, cap liability at $100 per package unless you purchase additional coverage. If your shipment contains items worth more than $100, relying on standard liability alone means you bear the risk for the difference.</p><p>Shipping insurance, by contrast, is a separate product that provides coverage up to the insured value in the event of documented loss or damage. Fast Express Shipping offers insurance coverage starting at 1.5% of the declared value, with a minimum premium of $5. For a shipment worth $1,000, the insurance premium would be approximately $15 — a small cost relative to the peace of mind it provides.</p><p>To file a successful insurance claim, you will need the original receipt or proof of value for the item, photographs of the damage if applicable, the original packaging for inspection, and the shipment tracking number. Claims must be filed within 30 days of the scheduled delivery date. Our claims team processes most claims within 5–10 business days.</p><p>We strongly recommend purchasing insurance for any shipment with contents valued over $200, including electronics, jewelry, artwork, and documents with replacement costs. The insurance option is available during the shipment request process. Contact our support team if you have questions about coverage levels or exclusions.</p>',
                'published_at' => Carbon::now()->subDays(80),
