            [
                'title' => 'How to Read Your Shipment Tracking Information',
                'slug' => Str::slug('How to Read Your Shipment Tracking Information'),
                'excerpt' => 'Tracking statuses and codes can be confusing. This guide explains every tracking milestone you might encounter and what it means for your shipment.',
                'body' => '<p>Real-time tracking is one of the most valued features in modern shipping, but the statuses displayed in tracking systems are not always intuitive. Understanding what each status means can save you from unnecessary worry and help you take the right action if something unexpected happens.</p><p>The first status you will see after submitting a shipment is "Shipment Created" or "Label Generated." This means we have received your request and a tracking number has been assigned, but the physical package has not yet been collected. "Picked Up" or "Collected" means a courier has physically taken the package from the drop-off location or your scheduled pickup address. Once the package enters our sorting facility, you will see "Processing at Origin Facility."</p><p>"In Transit" means your package is moving through our carrier network toward its destination. You may see multiple "In Transit" updates as the package passes through intermediate facilities. "Arrived at Destination Country" indicates the package has landed in the destination country and is awaiting customs clearance. "Customs Clearance in Progress" means the package is being reviewed by customs authorities — this is normal and usually takes 1–3 days.</p><p>"Out for Delivery" is one of the most anticipated statuses — it means your package is on a delivery vehicle and will be delivered that day during normal business hours. "Delivery Attempted" means the courier tried to deliver but no one was available to receive the package. Most carriers will attempt delivery again the next business day, or you may be asked to arrange a pickup from a local depot.</p><p>If you see "Exception," it means something unexpected has occurred — this could be an incorrect address, a damaged label, a customs hold, or a missed connection. An exception does not mean your package is lost; in most cases, our support team is already working on a resolution. Always check your email when an exception status appears, as we will send you specific information about what happened and what steps are being taken.</p>',
                'published_at' => Carbon::now()->subDays(120),
                'is_published' => true,
