            [
                'title' => 'Understanding Freight Class: A Guide for Commercial Shippers',
                'slug' => Str::slug('Understanding Freight Class: A Guide for Commercial Shippers'),
                'excerpt' => 'Freight class determines how LTL shipments are priced and handled. Understanding it can save your business significant money on commercial shipping.',
                'body' => '<p>If you ship commercial freight via LTL (less-than-truckload) carriers, freight class is one of the most important concepts to understand. Freight class is a standardized classification system used by North American carriers to set pricing for LTL shipments. It is determined by four factors: density, stowability, handling difficulty, and liability (the risk of damage or theft).</p><p>The National Motor Freight Classification (NMFC) defines 18 freight classes ranging from Class 50 (the least expensive, for dense, durable goods like metal hardware) to Class 500 (the most expensive, for low-density, high-value, or difficult-to-handle items). Most commercial goods fall somewhere in the middle. Common examples: palletized beverages are Class 60–70, boxed electronics are Class 100–150, and assembled furniture is often Class 125–150.</p><p>Density is the primary driver of freight class. The formula is simple: weight in pounds divided by cubic feet of space occupied. A shipment that weighs 500 lbs and occupies 10 cubic feet has a density of 50 lbs per cubic foot, which corresponds roughly to Class 50 or 60. Shippers often make the mistake of reporting the wrong dimensions, resulting in a class reclassification at the carrier\'s facility and an unexpected invoice adjustment.</p><p>Always measure your freight accurately and honestly. If a carrier inspects your shipment and determines the actual class is higher than declared, you will receive an invoice adjustment that is often significantly higher than the original quote. Building accurate dimensions and weights into your shipping workflow from the start eliminates these surprises.</p><p>Fast Express Shipping\'s freight quoting tool automatically calculates the recommended freight class based on the dimensions and weight you enter. Our commercial shipping team is also available to help classify unusual items and ensure you are getting the best rate for your specific freight characteristics. Contact us for a free freight shipping consultation.</p>',
                'published_at' => Carbon::now()->subDays(160),
                'is_published' => true,
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'Fast Express Shipping\'s Response to Supply Chain Disruptions',
                'slug' => Str::slug('Fast Express Shippings Response to Supply Chain Disruptions'),
                'excerpt' => 'Global supply chains face ongoing disruptions. Here is how Fast Express Shipping is adapting to protect our customers\' shipments and delivery timelines.',
                'body' => '<p>The past several years have demonstrated that global supply chains are more vulnerable to disruption than many businesses previously assumed. Port congestion, geopolitical tensions, extreme weather events, and capacity shortfalls have all created real challenges for international shipping. Fast Express Shipping has responded by building resilience into every layer of our operations.</p><p>Our primary adaptation has been carrier diversification. Rather than depending on a small number of large carriers for the bulk of our volume, we have distributed our shipment flows across a wider range of air cargo, ocean freight, and ground transportation providers. When one carrier experiences disruptions — as happened during the Red Sea shipping crisis — we can reroute volume to alternative carriers with minimal impact to customers.</p><p>We have also invested in increased advance planning capability. Our operations team now uses predictive analytics to identify potential disruptions 7–14 days in advance based on weather data, geopolitical news, port congestion metrics, and carrier capacity information. When a risk is identified, we proactively reroute shipments and notify affected customers before delays actually occur rather than after.</p><p>Transparent communication is central to our disruption response. When delays are unavoidable, we notify customers immediately with specific information about the cause, the revised timeline, and the steps we are taking. We have learned that customers are far more forgiving of delays when they are informed promptly and given accurate updates than when they discover delays on their own.</p><p>We continue to monitor global logistics conditions daily and update our service advisories on the Service Alerts page of our website. If you have a time-sensitive shipment and want to discuss current conditions on a specific route, our operations team is available to provide a candid assessment and recommend the best service option given current conditions.</p>',
