            [
                'title' => 'What Is an HS Code and Why Does It Matter for Your Shipment?',
                'slug' => Str::slug('What Is an HS Code and Why Does It Matter for Your Shipment'),
                'excerpt' => 'The Harmonized System code is a universal product classification used by customs authorities worldwide. Getting it right is essential for smooth international shipping.',
                'body' => '<p>If you have ever shipped goods internationally, you may have encountered a field labeled "HS Code" and wondered what it means. The Harmonized System (HS) is an internationally standardized system of names and numbers used by customs authorities in over 200 countries to classify traded products. Every physical good that crosses an international border should have an HS code assigned to it.</p><p>HS codes are structured hierarchically. The first two digits identify the chapter (broad product category), the next two identify the heading, and the following two identify the subheading. Countries can add further digits for domestic purposes. For example, HS 8471 refers to computers and peripheral equipment; 847130 specifically identifies portable computers weighing 10 kg or less.</p><p>Getting the HS code right matters for several reasons. First, duties and taxes are calculated based on the HS code — an incorrect code can result in overpayment or, worse, underpayment that is caught by customs and results in a penalty. Second, some HS codes are subject to import restrictions, licenses, or outright bans in certain countries. Knowing the code for your product in advance lets you verify compliance before shipping.</p><p>Finding the correct HS code for your goods is not always straightforward. The World Customs Organization publishes the official HS classification schedules, and most national customs authorities have search tools on their websites. Shipping platforms like Fast Express Shipping also have integrated HS code search tools that suggest the appropriate code based on your product description.</p><p>When in doubt, consult a customs broker. Misclassification is one of the most common compliance errors in international trade and can result in delays, fines, or seizure of goods. Our team of customs specialists can review your HS code selection at no charge as part of the shipment submission process. Reach out before you ship if you are uncertain about the correct classification for your goods.</p>',
                'published_at' => Carbon::now()->subDays(190),
                'is_published' => true,
            ],
            [
                'title' => 'The Benefits of Scheduled Pickup Service for Regular Shippers',
                'slug' => Str::slug('The Benefits of Scheduled Pickup Service for Regular Shippers'),
                'excerpt' => 'If your business ships packages regularly, scheduled pickup service eliminates the daily hassle of drop-off trips and helps streamline your logistics workflow.',
                'body' => '<p>For businesses that ship parcels on a daily or near-daily basis, visiting a drop-off location every day is an inefficient use of staff time. Fast Express Shipping\'s Scheduled Pickup service assigns a dedicated courier to collect your packages at a fixed time each business day, eliminating the logistics overhead and allowing your team to focus on higher-value activities.</p><p>Setting up Scheduled Pickup is straightforward. Business account holders can log into their dashboard and configure a preferred pickup window (morning, midday, or afternoon), a pickup address, and special access instructions if needed. Our system dispatches a courier automatically at the scheduled time. If on a particular day you have no packages to ship, you can cancel the pickup with two hours\' notice through the app or website.</p><p>Scheduled Pickup customers also benefit from later cutoff times. Packages collected via Scheduled Pickup are typically loaded into the same-day transit network up to two hours later than drop-off packages, giving businesses more time to prepare orders before they need to be shipped. For e-commerce businesses processing orders throughout the day, this extra window can make the difference between a customer receiving their order tomorrow versus the day after.</p><p>From a cost perspective, Scheduled Pickup is included at no additional charge for accounts shipping more than 10 packages per week. For lower-volume shippers, the service is available at a small weekly fee that most businesses find easily justified by the time saved. Our account managers can help you determine whether Scheduled Pickup makes sense for your shipping volume and patterns.</p><p>To set up Scheduled Pickup, log into your Business Account dashboard, navigate to the Pickup Settings section, and follow the setup wizard. If you do not yet have a Business Account, applying takes under five minutes and is free. Business accounts also unlock volume pricing, detailed analytics, and dedicated support.</p>',
